{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476157"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:41:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:41:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13655"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13655"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.46,0.15,0.21,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6260"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6260"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13655"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30241"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"731"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1860"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42901"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44157"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old male presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increasing exercise intolerance, fatigue, and occasional palpitations. He reports mild shortness of breath during physical activities. He was diagnosed with a congenital heart condition at birth but has not required any interventions. He does not take any regular medications. His paternal uncle has a history of arrhythmias. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His BMI is 22 kg/m2. Auscultation reveals a holosystolic murmur best heard at the left lower sternal border, accompanied by widely split S1 and S2 heart sounds. Echocardiography shows significant tricuspid valve regurgitation, apical displacement of the tricuspid leaflets (8 mm/m2), and right atrial enlargement. An ECG reveals sinus rhythm with a right bundle branch block and delta waves. Chest X-ray shows mild cardiomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tetralogy of Fallot","Ebstein anomaly","Atrial septal defect","Ventricular septal defect","Pulmonary stenosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEbstein anomaly\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the characteristic findings of apical displacement of the tricuspid valve leaflets, significant tricuspid regurgitation, and right atrial enlargement on echocardiography. This congenital heart defect involves malformation and displacement of the tricuspid valve leaflets into the right ventricle, resulting in \u0022atrialization\u0022 of the right ventricle and tricuspid regurgitation. Patients may present with exercise intolerance, fatigue, cyanosis, and arrhythmias, as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Edelta waves\u003C/strong\u003E and right bundle branch block on ECG suggests \u003Cstrong\u003EWolff-Parkinson-White (WPW) syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, a common arrhythmia associated with Ebstein anomaly due to accessory conduction pathways. WPW syndrome can cause palpitations and predispose patients to supra-ventricular tachycardias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETetralogy of Fallot\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with cyanosis due to right-to-left shunting from a combination of ventricular septal defect, pulmonary stenosis, right ventricular hypertrophy, and an overriding aorta, which are not prominent features in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E can cause right atrial enlargement and signs of right heart volume overload but does not typically involve displacement of the tricuspid valve, significant tricuspid regurgitation, or WPW syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with a holosystolic murmur best heard at the left lower sternal border due to left-to-right shunting. However, it is not associated with the specific tricuspid valve abnormalities or WPW syndrome seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a systolic ejection murmur at the left upper sternal border and potential right ventricular hypertrophy, rather than the tricuspid valve displacement, tricuspid regurgitation, and WPW syndrome observed here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ebstein anomaly often presents with tricuspid valve displacement, significant tricuspid regurgitation, and right atrial enlargement, distinguishable via echocardiography.","Wolff-Parkinson-White (WPW) syndrome is a common arrhythmia associated with Ebstein anomaly, seen as delta waves on ECG."],"references":["Possner M, Gensini FJ, Mauchley DC, Krieger EV, Steinberg ZL. Ebstein\u2019s anomaly of the tricuspid valve: an overview of pathology and management. Current Cardiology Reports. 2020 Dec;22:1-7.                                   https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11886-020-01412-z"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30241"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13655"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30241"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-13T17:41:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-12T09:04:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6260"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45328"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64